{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/simplest-guide-for-regular-expressions-nlp-made-easy-bbb33cd694be", "time": 1683007771.213088, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/simplest-guide-for-regular-expressions-nlp-made-easy-bbb33cd694be/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Simple Guide to Regular Expressions | by Chirag Sharma | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Simple Guide to Regular Expressions", "description": "Regular Expression are among the best tools for NLP, Text Analytics, Cleaning. NLP Researchers use them to tokenize, lemmatize, and create powerful tools."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Regular expressions are considered hard and advanced level stuff if you don\u2019t know them but if you do, congrats, you know hard and advanced level stuff. In this post, we will uncover the basics of regular expressions and at the end, I have attached a link to my notebook where you can see three times more functionalities apart from the one we will discuss here.", "So let\u2019s start by defining regular expressions:", "A regular expression is a sequence of characters that define a search pattern.", "Regular expressions have wide use cases:", "Regular expressions play a vital role in your day to day coding tasks under the hood plus it\u2019s a super-powerful tool when it comes to data-cleaning, data-mining, and other operations that are too vast to hard-code. We create a regular expression pattern that is slid across the whole text and the matched part\u2019s location or value is returned to us.", "Regular expression pattern matching has two parts to it:", "1. Right pattern: it\u2019s about figuring out what we really want to match", "2. Right re function: It\u2019s related to the position. Whether we want to match the pattern at the beginning or anywhere. In case we want to split and substitute we have to change our re function as well.", "So now we have to figure out two things: what pattern to use, and what function to use.", "If a pattern matches the string a match object is returned, otherwise, None object is returned.", "In case of a match as in result_text1 match object is returned which has three properties:", "re.match can match only in the beginning and re.search can match anywhere but only the first match is returned. The reason is that re.search is designed to find whether a pattern exists in the string or not. In case we want all of the matches to be returned we use re.findall. In fact re.findall is by default for pattern matching since by various identifiers and conditioning it can behave as re.match & re.search.", "Let\u2019s say we want to replace all occurrences of coronavirus with COVID-19. For this purpose we use re.sub re.sub(pattern,replacement,text,count) : the pattern is what we are trying to match, replacement is what to replace the pattern with and text is what we are searching pattern in. Set Count in case of substituting the limited number of occurrences. By default, it substitutes all occurrences.", "re.split(pattern,string,maxsplit,flags) pattern and string are usual parameters. maxsplit means how many split at max we want to do, by default it means all. We will talk about flags later", "String is split everywhere the pattern is matched. Since the above string has two corona occurrences it just split it at two places and hence resulting in three parts. A list of splits is returned.", "Regular expressions are excellent weapons again text-cleaning, text-mining, and doing complex stuff in one-liners.", "For remaining functionalities check out my Github notebook. Other advanced features of regular expressions are discussed there:", "Follow me on twitter for more updates on Natural Language Processing, Deep Learning, and Text Analytics:", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Head of Engineering @ Alchemy Group(Dubai), Ex-Founding Engineer @ Bytelearn AI, Ex Founder @ BlackNet"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canoni